<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25187a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25187a">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25187a"> 187(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Orthodo. leav. bread / eu Passover</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The East had always followed the fourth gospel in believing that Jesus was crucified on the day of the Passover. <mark>The West</mark> followed the other three gospels in believing that the Last Supper was the <mark>Passover</mark>, and they consequently used <mark>unleavened bread, while the Greeks used leavened</mark>. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 334</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Camel bedouins regarded bread as a dainty and ate it only about once a month. Some tribes eat leavened bread only during the rainy season and unleavened bread (falir) during the dry season.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14127b" href="c14all.htm#c14127b">VI.C.14:127(b)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
